  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_9",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: logistic regression (binary outcome). When the outcome is yes/no rather than a number, linear regression is the wrong tool — logistic regression models the PROBABILITY of the outcome. Read the coefficient table as ODDS RATIOS with 95% confidence intervals: an odds ratio above 1 means the predictor raises the odds of the outcome, below 1 lowers them, and a CI that does not cross 1 is 'significant' (matching the Wald p-value). The model-level fit is the likelihood-ratio test (does the model beat the intercept-only null?) and McFadden's pseudo-R². The fit plot shows the predicted probability against the linear predictor η = Xβ — the classic S-curve, which generalises to ANY number of predictors — with the observed 0/1 outcomes overlaid so you can see the separation. Watch for a non-convergence warning: it usually signals separation (a predictor splits the outcome perfectly), which makes the estimates unreliable. Cox (1958); Hosmer & Lemeshow (2000).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
  ],
